---
import Layout from "@layouts/Layout.astro";
import SectionHeader from "@components/SectionHeader.astro";
import { u } from "@/lib/url";
---

<Layout title="About · Agentic Skill Auditor">
  <SectionHeader
    eyebrow="author · context · how to read this site"
    title="About"
  />

  <!-- 60-second tour -->
  <section class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-sm uppercase tracking-[0.16em] text-ink-500 font-medium mb-4">
      60-second tour
    </h2>
    <div class="border border-ink-200 rounded-md bg-white p-6">
      <ol class="space-y-3 text-sm leading-relaxed text-ink-700">
        <li class="flex gap-3">
          <span class="font-mono text-accent-700 font-semibold tabular shrink-0 w-6">1.</span>
          <div>
            Start on the <a href={u("/")}>Overview</a> for the headline numbers, the
            bimodal F1 figure, and the constructive answer to "can sandbox policy
            be derived from skill markdown alone?"
          </div>
        </li>
        <li class="flex gap-3">
          <span class="font-mono text-accent-700 font-semibold tabular shrink-0 w-6">2.</span>
          <div>
            Browse the <a href={u("/findings")}>15 findings (A–O)</a> grouped by the three
            structural patterns. Click into any finding for its narrative + key
            numbers + related skills.
          </div>
        </li>
        <li class="flex gap-3">
          <span class="font-mono text-accent-700 font-semibold tabular shrink-0 w-6">3.</span>
          <div>
            For per-skill granularity: <a href={u("/skills")}>/skills</a> sortable table.
            Each skill row links to a drill-down page with SKILL.md, three predictions
            side-by-side, observed trace, and (for 5 skills) a registry-deployable
            policy bundle.
          </div>
        </li>
        <li class="flex gap-3">
          <span class="font-mono text-accent-700 font-semibold tabular shrink-0 w-6">4.</span>
          <div>
            The interactive <a href={u("/mutation-suite")}>mutation suite</a> shows
            6 attack patterns × 4 defense layers; click any cell for the per-mutation
            detail. The brittleness ablation under realistic regex regimes is at the bottom.
          </div>
        </li>
        <li class="flex gap-3">
          <span class="font-mono text-accent-700 font-semibold tabular shrink-0 w-6">5.</span>
          <div>
            The <a href={u("/policy")}>constructive policy direction</a> page documents
            the layered policy stack and lists the five generated <code>skill-policy.json</code>
            bundles inline (browseable, copy-paste-deployable).
          </div>
        </li>
        <li class="flex gap-3">
          <span class="font-mono text-accent-700 font-semibold tabular shrink-0 w-6">6.</span>
          <div>
            For the audit's design and statistical foundations: <a href={u("/methodology")}>/methodology</a>.
            For the rendered figures with full captions: <a href={u("/figures")}>/figures</a>.
          </div>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Author -->
  <section class="mb-12" id="author">
    <h2 class="text-sm uppercase tracking-[0.16em] text-ink-500 font-medium mb-4">
      Author
    </h2>
    <div class="border border-ink-200 rounded-md bg-white p-6">
      <div class="text-2xl font-semibold text-ink-950 mb-1">Rayhan Putra</div>
      <div class="text-ink-600">
        KTH MSc Cybersecurity (Autumn 2026 admit) · ITB STI 2021
      </div>
      <p class="mt-4 text-sm text-ink-700 leading-relaxed max-w-2xl">
        This audit was completed as the entry-point exercise for Professor Monperrus's
        open thesis topic <em>Automatic Hardening of Agentic Skills</em> (KTH ASSERT)
        as part of evaluation for a paid 4-month research-engineering role.
      </p>
      <p class="mt-3 text-sm text-ink-700 leading-relaxed max-w-2xl">
        Background: DevSecOps engineering at SwipeRx (multi-tool SAST/DAST/Trivy
        gating with severity-based remediation SLAs); BSc thesis on agentic AI
        for SIEM alert triage with anomaly-detection ML. The audit's empirical
        findings continue both lines, transposed onto the skill-registry trust
        problem as the supply-chain-side instance of the same trust gap that
        npm / Maven / PyPI face — but with worse exposure because skill discovery
        and binding can happen at execution time rather than build time.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- For Professor Monperrus -->
  <section class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-sm uppercase tracking-[0.16em] text-ink-500 font-medium mb-4">
      For Professor Monperrus
    </h2>
    <div class="border border-accent-300 bg-accent-50/30 rounded-md p-6">
      <p class="text-sm text-ink-800 leading-relaxed max-w-2xl">
        This site is companion to the
        <a href="#report"><strong>full report (PDF)</strong></a>; it does not replace it.
        The exercise prompt + verbatim 2026-05-04 email are in <code>README.md</code>;
        decision-log + alternatives-rejected in <code>decision-log.md</code>; methodology
        spine in <code>methodology.md</code>. The repository's <code>HANDOVER.md</code>
        is the single best file to read first if you'd like a five-minute orientation.
      </p>
      <p class="text-sm text-ink-800 leading-relaxed max-w-2xl mt-3">
        Section 8 of the report maps the audit's findings onto your three named
        subgoals (capability-based permission models, sandboxing granularities, detection
        methods combining static + semantic). Future work the audit anticipates,
        in priority order: cross-agent dynamic on the full 25 skills (currently n=7);
        TLS interception via mitmproxy; live policy enforcement via iptables-in-netns
        (recipe ready, deployment deferred); predictor extensions for the L2 misses
        (M4 bundled-sibling, M6 dependency-confusion); Tetragon/Falco-class runtime
        observability for CI-integrated per-skill-PR audit.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Sources -->
  <section class="mb-12" id="repo">
    <h2 class="text-sm uppercase tracking-[0.16em] text-ink-500 font-medium mb-4">
      Sources
    </h2>
    <div class="border border-ink-200 rounded-md bg-white p-6 space-y-3 text-sm">
      <div id="report">
        <div class="font-semibold text-ink-900">Full report (≈14 pages PDF)</div>
        <p class="text-ink-700 mt-0.5">
          <code>report.md</code> in the audit repository · 9 sections + abstract · ~9300 words.
          Companion <code>EXECUTIVE_SUMMARY.md</code> for a 1-page TL;DR;
          <code>SKILL_AUTHORING_GUIDE.md</code> for community-facing six-practice checklist.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div>
        <div class="font-semibold text-ink-900">Audit repository</div>
        <p class="text-ink-700 mt-0.5">
          Private GitHub repository with full source, traces, predictions, analyses,
          and harness. Access is granted on request; the dashboard you are reading
          is generated entirely from the repo's data.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div>
        <div class="font-semibold text-ink-900">This dashboard</div>
        <p class="text-ink-700 mt-0.5">
          Built with Astro 5 + Tailwind 4. Reads the audit's per-skill JSON,
          analysis JSON, and figure SVGs at build time. Open-source on the
          same repository under <code>dashboard/</code>; deployable to any static
          host. The dashboard does <strong>not</strong> modify any audit content —
          it is a presentation layer only.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</Layout>
